{"parse":{"title":"Discourse topic","pageid":32581874,"revid":738800540,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>discourse topic</b> is the central participant or idea of a stretch of connected discourse or dialogue. The <i>topic</i> is what the discourse is about. The notion is often confused with the related notion of sentence-level <a href=\"/wiki/Topic%E2%80%93comment\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Topic\u2013comment\">topic/theme</a>, which is frequently defined as \"what the sentence is about\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Discourse topics have been of considerable interest to linguists because of the relations between the topic of a discourse and various aspects of the grammatical structure of the sentence, including strategies for referent-tracking (including the use of <a href=\"/wiki/Grammatical_voice\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Grammatical voice\">voice</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Inversion_(linguistics)\" title=\"Inversion (linguistics)\">inversion</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Switch-reference\" title=\"Switch-reference\">switch-reference</a> markers, and <a href=\"/wiki/Obviative\" title=\"Obviative\">obviation</a>), topic-chaining, and pronominalization.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Discourse_topic&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Sapir, Edward. 1921. <i>Language: An Introduction to the Study of Speech.</i> New York: Harcourt, Brace.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Giv\u00f3n, Talmy (Ed.) (1994), <i>Voice and Inversion</i>. Amsterdam: John Benjamins.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Z\u00fa\u00f1iga, Fernando (2006) <i>Deixis and Alignment. Inverse systems in indigenous languages of the Americas.</i> Amsterdam: John Benjamins.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Linguistics_stub.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Linguistics_stub.svg/40px-Linguistics_stub.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"17\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Linguistics_stub.svg/60px-Linguistics_stub.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Linguistics_stub.svg/80px-Linguistics_stub.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"175\" data-file-height=\"74\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Sociolinguistics\" title=\"Sociolinguistics\">sociolinguistics</a> article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Discourse_topic&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Sociolinguistics-stub\" title=\"Template:Sociolinguistics-stub\"><abbr title=\"View this template\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:Sociolinguistics-stub\" title=\"Template talk:Socioli